Hello, everybody!

Some time ago somebody in this newsgroup asked about a description of
SHA. Unfortunately, recently we switched to new version of tin and a
new news server, and it seems that I have lost the message. Anyway,
here is a reply, sort of.

I collected in one archive the NIST document that describes SHA, Peter
Gutmann's implementation of SHA, and an example driver program that
uses it to compute SHA hashes of strings, files, etc., much in the
same way as the program MDxDRVR in the document describing MD[45]
does.

The archive is available from our anonymous ftp site:

ftp.informatik.uni-hamburg.de:/pub/virus/texts/crypto/shs.zip

The current makefile uses gcc to compile the program. Improvements are
welcome - for instance, to make the source/makefile compiler- and
prototype-independent; to eliminate the need to define the endianness
of the target machine at compile time, etc.

Regards,
Vesselin
